description._content: This past summer, I created a series of landscapes of the San Francisco Skyline at dawn from a little beach in Sausalito. I recently saw a fellow Flickr photographer's image taken from a similar spot on a different beautiful morning, which inspired me to go back and look at the shots I had taken. photo.title: We Are the Champions!

description._content: The Financial District, and much of the city has been lit in orange during the MLB playoffs and the World Series. Nick and I decided to shoot this iconic shot during Game 7 of the World Series. Not knowing if the Giants were going to win or lose, we wanted to capture the Trans America Building with the orange beacon, and Coit Tower lit in orange before it all came to an end. Fortunately the Giants won a hard fought series that won't be forgotten anytime soon. Winning the World Series 3 times in 5 years is an amazing feat, and will be recorded in history forever. I'm glad to have captured a single moment in San Francisco on the night the Giants won their third World Series. Thanks for looking! 21mm @ 15 sec @ F/11 @ ISO 100

photo.title: Giant Moon

description._content:
With last night's break from baseball, I took the bike for a quick cruise out to Treasure Island to check out orange-covered skyline, only to find that it was too windy for a good photo, and I was about 2 hours early to catch the moon low on the horizon. The peace and quiet was refreshing, though, so I took a chance and hung out at the Treasure Island Bar and Grill for a bit and waited for the moon to drop. Lucky me, by the time the moon had come down a bit, the wind had stopped and conditions were lovely for a few photos of the waterfront.  Things have a way of working out if given a little patience. (Of course, I first tried to get this shot with my film SLR and the battery promptly died, so I suppose the second lesson is to always have a backup plan.)


Let's go Giants! Finish this in 6 tonight.

photo.title: "Department Store"

description._content:
I took a stroll up to one of San Francisco's most recognized landmarks, the 1933-built, art deco-themed Coit Tower on Telegraph Hill. Inside are incredibly beautiful Diego Rivera-inspired, hand painted murals depicting life in San Francisco and California during the 1930's. The murals were recently lovingly restored and their vivid color and detail shines anew. This particular one is entitled "Department Store" which depicts the delights of shopping for music, toys, and wine, along with a refreshment stop at the fountain. I love the imagery of this amazing art! Come check these out this and the other gorgeous murals the next chance you get!

‪#‎AlwaysSF‬ — at Coit Tower.

description._content: This was taken last night on a last-minute, 20-hour escape to Angel Island. There are only nine reservable campsites on the entire island, and after the last ferry to the 'mainland' left at 5pm, it felt like we had the entire island to ourselves (plus a lot of deer and raccoon friends). We had dinner on an awesome beach entirely to ourselves, with this view of San Francisco & Alcatraz, and the bonus of a setting crescent moon over the Golden Gate. The night was balmy, still, and full of stars. What an amazing getaway!

photo.title: Super Harvest Moon - Sept 8, 2014

description._content:
I was planning to shoot a long-time-planned full-moon comp when I left the office today. However the sky was getting overcast when I drove from the south, so I had kept asking myself if it is a right decision to head to the city or just shoot it in the clear-sky east Bay. Luckily the sky was opened a little bit when I arrived at the south of GGB. I decided to stop at  Presidio. It took about 30 minutes from the moonrise to the moon disappeared into the above thick clouds. Here is one of lucky shots tonight. One single shoot with one exposure only!
Happy Moon Festival to Everyone!

photo.title: Coit Tower, Pioneer Park, Telegraph Hill, San Francisco, Ca. USA

description._content:
The elegant 64m-tall Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, a simple white column nesting three unpainted concrete cylinders, was designed by Arthur Brown Jr. (also architect of San Francisco City Hall) and built at the summit of Telegraph Hill, soon becoming one of San Francisco's major landmarks; its public observation platform, 54 m above the hilltop (141 m asl), is a popular tourist attraction.

A somewhat eccentric socialite, Lillie Hitchcock Coit was a life-long supporter of the local volunteer fire companies, becoming an honorary firefighter as mascot of Knickerbocker Engine Co. 5 and actually assisting in call-outs.  At her death in 1929, a third of her estate, $118,000, was left to the city for civic beautification.  This funded a statue commemorating firefighters and, with a further $7,000 from city funds, this Art Deco tower on Telegraph Hill, which was completed and dedicated in October 1933.  Its resemblance to a firehose's nozzle is apparently coincidental.

In 1934, as a 'New Deal' federal programme to give artists gainful employment through the production of public artworks, the interior of the Tower's base was painted with murals by 27 artists, most from the California School of Fine Arts.  Depicting life in California during the Depression, some of the subject matter was controversial and was even painted-over before the opening.

The 87m asl hill between Fisherman's Wharf and the Financial District was first developed in 1850, when a semaphore signalling station was established to report on the arrival of ships.  Within three years it had been replaced by an electric telegraph station, which itself soon fell out of use, though the name stuck.  The site was purchased by local businessmen in 1876 specifically to prevent further development; they donated the land to the city on condition that it became a park.  Aside from being an obvious choice for the location of the commemorative tower, Pioneer Park is also known for its resident wild parrots.

Though Coit Tower is a San Francisco Designated Landmark, on the National Register of Historic Places, technically the site of the telegraph station carries the status of a California Historical Landmark, not the Tower.

Seen from the Alcatraz ferry terminal at Pier 33.
